    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-03-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-02-11T00:00:00-05:00"
                n="[Unnumbered document following Document 710 (#148)]" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d710a-148">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Editor’s Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>—No official record pertaining to this conversation has been found. <persName
                        corresp="#p_BJF1">Byrnes</persName> (<hi rend="italic">Speaking
                    Frankly</hi>, page 85) states that he told <persName corresp="#p_MVM1"
                        >Molotov</persName> on July 31 that there were three outstanding issues at
                    the Conference: reparations from Germany, Polish administration of a part of the
                    Soviet zone of occupation in Germany, and admission of Italy and the Balkan
                    states to the United Nations. He states further that he submitted a proposal
                    containing the only concessions which the United States was willing to
                        make;<note n="3" xml:id="d710a-148fn3">This may refer to a paper on
                        reparations from Germany. See <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                            target="#pg_512">p. 512, footnote 2</ref>. The United States position on
                        the other two questions at issue had been given to <persName
                            corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> by <persName corresp="#p_BJF1"
                            >Byrnes</persName> on July 30. See <ref target="#d731">documents Nos.
                            731</ref> and <ref target="#d1152">1152</ref>, <hi rend="italic"
                            >post</hi>, and see <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_480"
                            >p. 480</ref>.</note> that he asked <persName corresp="#p_MVM1"
                        >Molotov</persName> to present “the three proposals” to <persName
                        corresp="#p_SGIV1">Stalin</persName> so that they might be considered at the
                    meeting of the Heads of Government on July 31; that the United States “would
                    agree to all three or none”; and that he and <persName corresp="#p_TJV1"
                        >Truman</persName> would leave for the United States the next day.<note
                        n="4" xml:id="d710a-148fn4">Cf. <persName corresp="#p_BJF1"
                            >Byrnes</persName>, <hi rend="italic">All in One Lifetime</hi>, p.
                        302.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
